Not much exists, only the marriage records 1707-1836, T/R 168/1.

Ardleigh Parish Register

D/P 263/1/1, register of baptisms, marriages, and burials, 1555-1666, 35 images. I havenÕt taken the time to look at these, but I did browse through the marriages 1635-1640 and found no French. However, a Robert French was living in Ardleigh in 1641, after the Great Migration.

Assington Parish Register (Suffolk)

The Assington BishopÕs Transcripts cover a few years after 1564. Assington Parish Register of St. EdmundÕs Parish start in 1598. Baptisms and burials start in 1598, and marriages start in 1599 according to researcher Peter Nutt at the ERO. These records were searched for any French entries from the earliest records available to 1650 by researcher Ray Whitehand in Suffolk. The earliest church register begins in 1598. As some of the pages on the fiche copy of this register are faded beyond legibility, the archivist allowed Ray Whitehand to access the original register in October 2010. With regard to records before 1598, there are some registers bills available for Assington. Ray listed those available (on microfilm) below together with the identifying film codes. I donÕt know if you are familiar with these bills. They are notoriously difficult and time consuming to read. The single sheets (as presented by individual parishes to the archdeacon annually) are arranged on the film by year, then hundred, and parish. As the parishes are not in any alphabetical order it is a painstaking to search through the 20 to 30 parishes for the one required. One year at a time.

The marriage of Catherine French and an unknown event of Julyan French could not be located in Assington. However Ray checked out the marriage of Catherine French to John Ansell in BoydÕs Marriage Indexes for the county. While there was not an entry for Catherine French in the female index, he did identify an entry for John Ansell to a Katherine (surname not given) in Bures St Mary in 1558/59. Frustratingly it does not identify the surname of the bride, but as you have mentioned other French entries in this parish, I am wondering if this is in fact the marriage in question.

Because there are no records from 1636 to 1650 in Assington, this clearly indicates another reason to prove that this entire family immigrated to America.

Mount Bures Parish Register (Essex)

D/P 376/1/1 (1599-1711) and D/P 281/1/1 (1540-1773 – 63 images). These images are ONLY of Mount Bures in Essex, just moments over the border from Bures St. Mary in Suffolk.

Essex Researcher Janet Smith says there is a gap in the register from 1604-1611. After that the name French does not appear. No French burials in Bures St. Mary to 1604.

In the early years, only about 2 people are born yearly, and many years, no one was born, got married, or died. Bures St. Mary is on both sides of the Stour River. It is referred to as Mont Bures in Essex, and no one from this family is in these parish registers. They are all probably from the Suffolk side of the Stour River. It doesnÕt seem as though any French is listed in the D/P 281/1/1 register.

Colchester Parish Register

D/P 203/1/1, D/P 203/1/2, and D/P 203/1/3
St. BotolphÕs Church

There are many parish registers from Colchester. Since we know the French family belonged to St. BotolphÕs Church, I am not researching Berechurch, Bradfield, Brightlingsea, Holy Trinity, All Saints, St. Mary Magdalen, Chignal St. James, Chignal Smealey, Chickney, Chigwell, St. Mary the Virgin, St. Mary-at-the-Walls, Liston, Littlebury, Loughton, Maldon, Hadleigh, Hadstock, Gt. Hallingbury, or others.

The Register of St. BotolphÕs Church was in the care of All Saints Parish for nearly 300 years before it was returned by the rector in 1936. Christenings start in 1560. From ca. 1650 to 1836, the church was in ruins and most baptisms and marriages were recorded at All Saints Church during this period (I am not researching this period). We are looking for a William or John who were christened about 1580 at St. BotolphÕs.

D/P 203/1/1 has 84 images, 1560-1664, and only the last 2 images are of burials; no marriages that I could find. Marriages are on Image 26. Births start on Image 5. Marriages start on Image 23 – only need until Image 32.

D/P 203/1/2, 1667-1685 is too late

D/P 203/1/3, 1680-1799 is too late.

Marriage transcript available 1560-1631, also in BoydÕs Marriage Index 1560-1688 per Peter Nutt.

This mean that Elizabeth French who currently was living in Colchester married Bartholomew Burgess of Nayland on 28 Dec 1624. St. Nicholas was a parish church.

Colne Engaine Parish Register

Researcher Peter C. Nutt reports in 1998 Òno French baptisms 1629-1635Ó. He checked only the baptisms at first to see if any French lived in that particular parish, and if none existed, the marriage and burial records were not checked. No registers survived before 1629.

These records have been found now by Mara French in 2010 for the years 1605-1690, D/P 88/1/1 (36 images), and 1629-1762 D/P 193/1/1. I looked over these records and found several early entries for the Syday family who married into the John French family, FFA Chart #E3. In Sept 2010 I checked all records thru 1636, Image 11, and found no French although the writing was fairly easy to read. I suppose someday all these names will be in a searchable database.

Q/SR 252/70, John French, collier, to keep the peace to Margaret Crabb, widow, 19 Dec 1625.

Q/SR 253/20, John French of Colne Engaine, husbandman, 12 Apr 1626, kept a common alehouse (tavern) there without license.

T/A 418/105/5, John French of Colne Engaine, yeoman, indictment, 13 Jul 1629.

Copland Parish Register

D/P 186/1/1, Baptisms 1558-1760, Marriages 1558-1754, Burials 1558-1760. 72 images.
St. Michael and All Angels. These pages are quite mixed up and difficult to search. I checked baptism records between 1630-1636 and did not find any French.

Dagenham Parish Register

Need to check. Register covers period from 1598-1668. 60 images. The church is St. Peter and St. Paul. I checked quickly the baptisms from 1618 to 1637 (image 6 to 12). They were very easy to read. No French. It seemed plausible that some children would be baptized here before setting out to America, because Dagenham is along the docks just east of London. If there had been a French, I would have searched longer. The name French does appear later in the 1800s.

Finchingfield Parish Register

Chris N. French found just one marriage and one baptism prior to 1635 in Finchingfield. Records of a French at the ERO include:
Will of Richard French, yeoman, 1726, D/AMW 13/2/12
Will of William French, husbandman, 3 Jul 1640, D/AMW 2/52. He died on 25 Jun 1640 according to the Finchingfield parish register, Image 21. These dates do not coincide.

Precept, Thomas French of Arkesden, yeoman, 1562, Q/SR 5/32
Indictment, Peter French, 1662, T/A 418/156/75

Parish Register of Finchingfield, D/P 14/1/1, 1617-1708, 77 images

William French, widower, and Martha Crofley, married 1 Feb 1624/25, Image 8
Margarett French, wife of William, buried 26 Oct 1624, Image 8
William French, buried 25 Jun 1640, Image 21

Fordham Parish Register

Q/SR 234/132, John French, husbandman, recognizances, 2 Oct 1621. Parish register is from 1563-1730, D/P 372/1/1
It includes 59 images. I checked baptisms from 1621 to 1638, images 10-14. No French. Easy to read.

Foxearth Parish Register

D/P 368/1/1. Register is from 1551-1617. IÕd rather check a parish register from 1625-1635, the era right before the Great Migration, but none is available. Perhaps the microfilms of the transcripts are available for later on. Q/SR 264/61 shows a record of recognizances of William French, John Ellingham, and Henry Ellingham, all weavers, and John Ellingham to keep the peace to Elizabeth Evans, all of Foxearth, 1628. Could William French of FFA Chart #2 have married Elizabeth Evans?

There was an Edward Ellingham of Foxearth, laborer, who made his will on 26 Dec 1620 in Foxearth, D/AMW 3/92. Only 6 images appear. The name Ellingham appears many times in the parish register, first mentioned in 1551. Foxearth is very close to the Suffolk border and near Bildeston, Suffolk, where the John French of FFA Chart #4 lived. No French appears in this Foxearth parish register up until 1617 which shows only baptisms. The register is quite clear and easy to read.

Great Maplestead Parish Register

Records in Great Maplestead to 1650

The Great Maplestead Parish Register did not appear until 1651; baptisms and marriages began in 1697, and burials in 1678. Apparently earlier than 1651 no parish was established in that village; therefore, the parish records may be found in a nearby town with a church.

Wakes Colne Parish Register

Researcher Peter C. Nutt reports in 1998 Òno French baptisms 1604-1635Ó. He checked only the baptisms at first to see if any French lived in that particular parish, and if none existed, the marriage and burial records were not checked. Except for years 1550-1560, nothing survived before 1604.

Part of the Little Colne estate held of Robert Malet by Walter of Caen in 1086 extended into Wakes Colne where it formed the freehold or submanor of Serdeleshey or LOVENEY HALL. It was held of Colne Engaine manor until 1556 or later.  By the later 12th century William de Cheney or his successors had enfeoffed Richard Blunville, whose great nephew William Blunville disputed the estate with Richard Engaine between 1199 and 1201. Another William Blunville held c. 1278. By c. 1380 the estate was called Loveney Hall, pre- sumably from an owner; c. 1440 it belonged to a Culpepper. About 1503 Roger Draper sold 'Loveney Hall and Sherdelous' to Edward Sulyard,  and in 1546 Edward's son Eustace conveyed the estate, then called a manor, to William Sidey. Sidey at once sold part of the estate, later Great Loveney Hall, to John Newton, and the rest to John Sidey. John Sidey devised the manor to his son, another John, who sold it in 1574 to John Ball (d. 1602) and his son John (d. 1621). They were succeeded by another John Sidey, whose widow held in 1646 with her second husband Thomas Harlakenden. The estate, still called a manor in 1698 and 1711, was called Little Loveney Hall by 1730. It belonged to Osgood Hanbury (d. 1784) in 1768, and presumably descended with Inglesthorpes manor in White Colne to O. B. Hanbury (d. 1890). It was farmed by H. C. Crook in 1902, and belonged to his family in 1996.

Records in Great Maplestead to 1650

The Great Maplestead Parish Register did not appear until 1651; baptisms and marriages began in 1697, and burials in 1678. Apparently earlier than 1651 no parish was established in that village; therefore, the parish records may be found in a nearby town with a church. We have records of a French family living in Great Maplestead before 1651, but we have not found the parish to which this family belonged.

Bishop Transcripts

Parish registers began in 1538 of course not all registers have survived from this date. The Bishop Transcripts are a copy of the original parish register, copied by pen, pencil, or later by typewriter.

Many Incumbents were negligent in keeping parish registers so the Bishops ordered that the incumbents were to send copies of their registers each year to the Bishop this practice was made general in 1598. In almost any series of these transcripts there are annual gaps and also errors and omissions owing to insufficient care in copying. Essex has suffered very badly as regards to its BtÕs the main series starts in 1800 a number of parishes have BtÕs for 1629-30 & 1639-40 and some have years during the 1700Õs and the years 1810-1812 are missing for all parishes. Obviously you are interested in the 1600 years so you should order T/R 83
